And don't you just love these graphics?

00:03.698 --> 00:06.302
So here's time.

00:06.322 --> 00:10.630
And apparently it goes in both directions.

00:11.551 --> 00:13.896
And so does it go like this?

00:13.916 --> 00:18.664
I think what they mean is just time goes in this direction.

00:18.644 --> 00:22.668
And you're here and your upstream.

00:23.830 --> 00:25.411
So your upstream is your network.

00:25.692 --> 00:30.777
This is your network reading or your pre processing and the downstream, this is the GPU.

00:31.939 --> 00:40.228
So as you are pre processing things, you, you, um, and this should be, this should be different.

00:41.049 --> 00:45.073
It should mean, okay, to correct this right here.

00:45.173 --> 00:48.617
This is idle and this is running.

00:50.639 --> 00:53.443
So as your upstream processes images, right?

00:53.483 --> 01:00.492
At the beginning, your GPU is idle, but then as soon as it ships off the first batch of images, your GPU can run.

01:00.532 --> 01:01.533
Now it's running.

01:01.993 --> 01:13.768
While you're doing that, your upstream, your network is still reading new images, pre-processing them and so on, but it cannot, is too slow to insert a batch at the time that the GPU is done.

01:14.189 --> 01:20.477
The time the GPU is done, it's still processing this batch, so the GPU is idle.

01:20.457 --> 01:45.891
Until here where it finally manages to process that batch and then the GPU is running again I think that would have been a much better graphic But you know so their goal basically is that what you'll have is Right here for example after the batch what you'll do is you scrap this connection You take this and you put it into a smaller buffer

01:47.542 --> 01:50.256
And the buffer is a repeat buffer.

01:50.738 --> 01:53.552
So what it does is it simply will repeat.

01:56.317 --> 02:01.365
the whatever you have in the buffer until something new comes in, right?

02:01.385 --> 02:06.432
So new data point comes in, you just output that data point again, again, again, again.

02:06.492 --> 02:13.083
The for the GPU, it's going to feel like these are all new batches and they will continuously come in.

02:13.543 --> 02:21.295
But it's always the same until the next data point comes in, and then you output that one again, and again, and again, and again.

02:21.275 --> 02:28.233
Now the actual factor here you can of course tune by hand or you can just say repeat until something else comes in.

02:29.596 --> 02:36.634
In this paper they have an explicit factor where they say we repeat each data point four times or three times or so on.

02:36.614 --> 02:38.477
So this is data echoing.

02:38.537 --> 02:41.882
You basically echo the data point multiple times.

02:43.265 --> 02:46.790
And this can be done in various places.

02:47.171 --> 02:51.057
So they experiment with echoing in any of these places right here.

02:51.317 --> 02:58.088
So they experiment with it right here after reading and decoding, after shuffling.

02:59.170 --> 03:02.335
No, I think always before shuffling.

03:02.315 --> 03:11.957
Because if you have a shuffle buffer anyway, they say it makes sense that if you do the echoing, you do your shuffle buffer after your echoing.

03:11.977 --> 03:16.206
So here, then after augmentation and after batching.

03:16.473 --> 03:22.401
So they experiment with these three locations in echoing.

03:22.902 --> 03:25.545
Now, what could be the downturn of something like this?

03:26.006 --> 03:40.646
The downturn, of course, is that this SGD procedure right here, basically, it relies on the data incoming being an IID sample from your data distribution, right?

03:40.786 --> 03:45.332
That's how we formulate SGD, is that there's always new data incoming.

03:45.312 --> 03:53.421
Now, if you just output the same data point all the time, that is like no new information, first of all.

03:53.702 --> 04:06.797
And second of all, it could bias the SGD update, because it sees the same information over and over, it's going to think that's the whole data set.

04:06.777 --> 04:10.781
potentially it can make too many steps into the wrong direction.

04:11.661 --> 04:15.405
That just happens to be the bias in this particular data point.

04:16.205 --> 04:19.789
So the IID assumption is invalid.

04:21.270 --> 04:24.753
Now, why do you experiment with this in different locations?

04:24.913 --> 04:32.100
Because what you expect is that it hurts more or it hurts less the earlier you introduce this.

04:32.580 --> 04:36.784
So if you introduce echoing right here, so if you echo,

04:36.764 --> 04:43.278
your data until new data from the network comes in, it's still going to be shuffled differently, right?

04:43.659 --> 04:46.464
And it's still going to be augmented differently.

04:46.505 --> 04:57.608
So each time the data point comes out of the echo buffer, it is going to be shuffled and it is going to be augmented in a different way than the last time the same data point came out.

04:57.588 --> 05:01.473
And this is going to be batched together because you've shuffled differently.

05:01.833 --> 05:05.397
It's going to be batched together with a different bunch of data points.

05:05.517 --> 05:08.401
And that means SGD gets new information.

05:08.962 --> 05:24.080
But if you go onto the very last thing where you just after the batch right here, or you input the echo, that means SGD just gets to see the same batch of data augmented in the same way all the time, right?

05:24.961 --> 05:26.903
So the

05:26.883 --> 05:31.910
Of course, where you exactly have to echo, you have to trade this off.

05:32.270 --> 05:43.185
So you have to trade off the how much you basically violate the IID fresh data assumption against where in your data pipeline is the bottleneck.

05:43.205 --> 05:52.738
So if your bottleneck is in the data augmentation, it may make little sense to echo before that because your bottleneck is the data augmentation.

05:52.718 --> 06:00.216
And that being said, if the bottleneck is that you don't have enough GPUs, then it probably doesn't make sense to data echo at all.

06:00.960 --> 06:05.040
Though their experiments are somehow wonky on this.

